data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The configuration you used in .NET 10 (e.g., `AllowSynchronousIO = true` or similar) no longer exists. All synchronous LINQ operations throw `InvalidOperationException` with **no workaround**.

**Every method in your repository is affected:**

| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | `FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

## The fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` is still synchronous (it's an in-memory operation, no I/O) — that's fine.
- Callers of these methods must also be updated to `await` the results, which typically propagates `async` up the call chain to your controllers/endpoints.
- Remove the old sync-over-async opt-in from your `DbContext` configuration — it will cause a build error in EF Core 11.
